{"title_page": "Cabinet Secretary for Finance", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2012}}\n{{Infobox Political post\n|post            = Cabinet Secretary for Finance <br> R\u00f9naire a 'Chaibineit airson Ionmhais\n|body            = \n|insignia        = [[File:Scottish Government Logo.svg|250px]]\n|image           = [[File:KateForbesMSP-May2016.jpg]] \n|incumbent       = [[Kate Forbes]]\n|incumbentsince  = 17 February 2020\n|style           = Cabinet Secretary <br/> ''Finance Secretary'' <small>(within Scotland) <br/> ''Scottish Finance Secretary'' <small> (outwith Scotland)</small>\n|residence       =\n|appointer       = [[First Minister of Scotland|First Minister]]\n|formation       = July 1999\n|succession      =\n|inaugural       = [[Jack McConnell]] <br/> <small>Minister for Finance</small>\n|website         = {{URL|www.gov.scot}}\n}}\nThe '''Cabinet Secretary for Finance''', commonly referred to as the '''Finance Secretary''', is a member of the [[List of Scottish Governments|Cabinet]] in the [[Scottish Government]]. The Cabinet Secretary has Ministerial responsibility for the Scottish Government's [[Scottish Executive Finance Directorates|Finance Directorates]]. The post is currently held by [[Kate Forbes]] who replaced [[Derek Mackay]] on 17 February 2020.\n\n==History==\nFollowing [[devolution]] in 1999, the [[Dewar Government|Government of First Minister Donald Dewar]] instituted the position as the '''Minister for Finance''', which was renamed the '''Minister for Finance and Local Government''' in the [[McLeish Government|Government of Henry McLeish]] from 2000 to 2001. In the first [[First McConnell government|Government of Jack McConnell]], from 2001 to 2003, the position was renamed as the '''Minister for Finance and Public Services''', changed to the '''Minister for Finance and Public Service Reform''' after a reshuffle of the [[Second McConnell government]] in 2004. The first [[Government of the 3rd Scottish Parliament|Government of Alex Salmond]] in 2007 combined the Minister for Finance element, with that of Enterprise and Transport to create the '''Cabinet Secretary for Finance and Sustainable Growth'''. After the [[2011 Scottish Parliament election|2011 election]] the position was named '''Cabinet Secretary for Finance, Employment and Sustainable Growth''' and the transport portfolio was moved under the remit of [[Cabinet Secretary for Infrastructure, Investment and Cities|another]] Cabinet position. In November 2014, the [[first Sturgeon government]] renamed the position to '''Cabinet Secretary for Finance, Constitution and Economy''', and in 2016 it was again renamed to '''Cabinet Secretary for Finance and the Constitution'''. It was further renamed to Finance, Economy and Fair Work in June 2018, taking some additional responsibilities from the position of [[Cabinet Secretary for Economy, Jobs and Fair Work]] which was abolished, but losing some constitutional responsibilities to the [[Cabinet Secretary for Government Business and Constitutional Relations]].<ref name=june2018>{{cite web|url=https://news.gov.scot/news/new-cabinet-appointed|title=New Cabinet appointed|publisher=Scottish Government|date=2018-06-26|accessdate=2018-06-27}}</ref> The title was shortened to simply '''Cabinet Secretary for Finance''' in February 2020, with some responsibilities transferred over to the [[Cabinet Secretary for Economy, Fair Work and Culture]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.scot/news/cabinet-appointments/|title=Cabinet Appointments|publisher=Scottish Government|date=17 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Overview==\n\n===Responsibilities===\nAs Cabinet Secretary for Finance, Economy and Fair Work the responsibilities of the role were:\n\nScottish economy, inclusive growth, managing the public finances, fiscal policy and taxation, Scottish budget, budgetary monitoring and reporting, Government procurement, efficient government, National Performance Framework, public bodies policy, Scottish Futures Trust, Scottish Enterprise - national enterprise agency, trade and inward investment, trade unions, public sector pay, Scottish National Investment Bank, Registers of Scotland, digital economy and digital public services, public sector pensions, Innovation and increasing productivity, internationalisation and European Structural Funds, financial services, life sciences, low carbon economy, business, industry and manufacturing, employment policy, labour market strategy, the living wage and fair work, employability programmes, youth employment (including implementation of the Wood Commission recommendations), women's employment, Bankruptcy and Accountant in Bankruptcy (Scottish government agency), Regional Economic Forums, PACE, Consumer Protection.<ref name=\"june2018\"/>\n\n===Public bodies===\nThe following public bodies reported to the Cabinet Secretary for Finance, Economy and Fair Work:\n* [[Revenue Scotland]]\n* [[Scottish Futures Trust]]\n* [[Scottish National Investment Bank]]\n* [[Scottish Public Pensions Agency]]\n* [[Registers of Scotland]]\n\n==List of Office holders==\n{|class=\"wikitable\"  cellpadding=\"6\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin: 0 0 0 1em; background: #f9f9f9; border: 1px #aaaaaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; \"  \n|colspan=\"7\"|\n\n===Minister for Finance===\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Name\n! width=75|Portrait\n!Entered Office\n!Left Office\n!Party\n!First Minister\n|-\n|{{Scottish politics/party colours/Scottish Labour Party}}|\n|[[Jack McConnell]]\n| [[File:Jack McConnell.jpg|75px]]\n|19 May 1999\n|26 October 2000   \n|[[Scottish Labour Party]]\n\n|[[Donald Dewar]] \n|-\n|colspan=\"7\"|\n\n===Minister for Finance and Local Government===\n|-\n|{{Scottish politics/party colours/Scottish Labour Party}}|\n|[[Angus MacKay (Scottish politician)|Angus Mackay]]\n\n| [[File:Angus MacKay.jpg|75px]]\n|26 October 2000\n|22 November 2001   \n|[[Scottish Labour Party]]\n\n|[[Henry McLeish]]  \n|-\n|colspan=\"7\"|\n\n===Minister for Finance and Public Services===\n|-\n|{{Scottish politics/party colours/Scottish Labour Party}}|\n|[[Andy Kerr (Scottish politician)|Andy Kerr]]\n\n| [[File:Andy Kerr.jpg|75px]]\n|22 November 2001\n|4 October 2004   \n|[[Scottish Labour Party]]\n\n|[[Jack McConnell]]  \n|-\n|colspan=\"7\"|\n\n===Minister for Finance and Public Service Reform===\n|-\n|{{Scottish politics/party colours/Scottish Labour Party}}|\n|[[Tom McCabe]]\n\n| [[File:Tom McCabe.jpg|75px]]\n|4 October 2004\n|16 May 2007   \n|[[Scottish Labour Party]]\n\n|[[Jack McConnell]]  \n|-\n|colspan=\"7\"|\n\n===Cabinet Secretary for Finance and Sustainable Growth===\n|-\n|{{Scottish politics/party colours/Scottish National Party}}|\n|[[John Swinney]]\n\n| [[File:John Swinney, Cabinet Secretary for Sustainable Growth (1).jpg|75px]]\n|     17 May 2007\n|19 May 2011\n|[[Scottish National Party]]\n\n|[[Alex Salmond]]\n|-\n|colspan=\"7\"|\n\n===Cabinet Secretary for Finance, Employment and Sustainable Growth===\n|-\n|{{Scottish politics/party colours/Scottish National Party}}|\n|[[John Swinney]]\n\n| [[File:John Swinney, Cabinet Secretary for Sustainable Growth (1).jpg|75px]]\n|19 May 2011\n|21 November 2014\n\n|[[Scottish National Party]]\n|[[Alex Salmond]]\n|-\n|colspan=\"7\"|\n\n===Cabinet Secretary for Finance, Constitution and Economy===\n|-\n|{{Scottish politics/party colours/Scottish National Party}}|\n|[[John Swinney]]\n| [[File:John Swinney, Cabinet Secretary for Sustainable Growth (1).jpg|75px]]\n|21 November 2014\n|18 May 2016\n|[[Scottish National Party]]\n|[[Nicola Sturgeon]]\n|-\n|colspan=\"7\"|\n\n===Cabinet Secretary for Finance and the Constitution===\n|-\n|{{Scottish politics/party colours/Scottish National Party}}|\n|[[Derek Mackay]]\n|[[File:DerekMacKayMSP20110509.JPG|75px]]\n|18 May 2016\n|26 June 2018\n|[[Scottish National Party]]\n|[[Nicola Sturgeon]]\n|-\n|colspan=\"7\"|\n\n===Cabinet Secretary for Finance, Economy and Fair Work===\n|-\n|{{Scottish politics/party colours/Scottish National Party}}|\n|[[Derek Mackay]]\n|[[File:DerekMacKayMSP20110509.JPG|75px]]\n|26 June 2018\n|5 February 2020\n|[[Scottish National Party]]\n|[[Nicola Sturgeon]]\n|-\n|colspan=\"7\"|\n\n===Cabinet Secretary for Finance===\n|-\n|{{Scottish politics/party colours/Scottish National Party}}|\n|[[Kate Forbes]]\n|[[File:KateForbesMSP-May2016.jpg|75px]]\n|17 February 2020\n|Incumbent\n|[[Scottish National Party]]\n|[[Nicola Sturgeon]]\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Cabinet (government)]]\n*[[Minister (government)|Government Minister]]\n*[[Ministry (government department)|Ministry]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.scotland.gov.uk/Topics/Business-Industry Scottish Government - Business and Industry]\n*[http://www.scotland.gov.uk/Topics/Economy Scottish Government - Economy]\n*[http://www.scotland.gov.uk/Topics/Planning Scottish Government - Planning]\n*[http://www.scotland.gov.uk/Topics/Transport Scottish Government - Transport]\n\n{{Scottish Cabinet}}\n\n[[Category:Finance ministers of Scotland| ]]\n[[Category:Cabinet Secretary posts of the Scottish Government|Finance]]\n[[Category:Economy ministers]]\n[[Category:Transport ministers]]\n[[Category:Public finance of Scotland]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2012}}\n{{Infobox Political post\n|post            = Cabinet Secretary for Finance <br> R\u00f9naire a 'Chaibineit airson Ionmhais\n|body            = \n|insignia        = [[File:Scottish Government Logo.svg|250px]]\n|image           = [[File:KateForbesMSP-May2016.jpg]] \n|incumbent       = [[Kate Forbes]]\n|incumbentsince  = 17 February 2020\n|style           = Cabinet Secretary <br/> ''Finance Secretary'' <small>(within Scotland) <br/> ''Scottish Finance Secretary'' <small> (outwith Scotland)</small>\n|residence       =\n|appointer       = [[First Minister of Scotland|First Minister]]\n|formation       = July 1999\n|succession      =\n|inaugural       = [[Jack McConnell]] <br/> <small>Minister for Finance</small>\n|website         = {{URL|www.gov.scot}}\n}}\nThe '''Cabinet Secretary for Finance''', commonly referred to as the '''Finance Secretary''', is a member of the [[List of Scottish Governments|Cabinet]] in the [[Scottish Government]]. The Cabinet Secretary has Ministerial responsibility for the Scottish Government's [[Scottish Executive Finance Directorates|Finance Directorates]]. The post is currently held by [[Kate Forbes]] who replaced [[Derek Mackay]] on 17 February 2020.\n\n==History==\nFollowing [[devolution]] in 1999, the [[Dewar Government|Government of First Minister Donald Dewar]] instituted the position as the '''Minister for Finance''', which was renamed the '''Minister for Finance and Local Government''' in the [[McLeish Government|Government of Henry McLeish]] from 2000 to 2001. In the first [[First McConnell government|Government of Jack McConnell]], from 2001 to 2003, the position was renamed as the '''Minister for Finance and Public Services''', changed to the '''Minister for Finance and Public Service Reform''' after a reshuffle of the [[Second McConnell government]] in 2004. The first [[Government of the 3rd Scottish Parliament|Government of Alex Salmond]] in 2007 combined the Minister for Finance element, with that of Enterprise and Transport to create the '''Cabinet Secretary for Finance and Sustainable Growth'''. After the [[2011 Scottish Parliament election|2011 election]] the position was named '''Cabinet Secretary for Finance, Employment and Sustainable Growth''' and the transport portfolio was moved under the remit of [[Cabinet Secretary for Infrastructure, Investment and Cities|another]] Cabinet position. In November 2014, the [[first Sturgeon government]] renamed the position to '''Cabinet Secretary for Finance, Constitution and Economy''', and in 2016 it was again renamed to '''Cabinet Secretary for Finance and the Constitution'''. It was further renamed to Finance, Economy and Fair Work in June 2018, taking some additional responsibilities from the position of [[Cabinet Secretary for Economy, Jobs and Fair Work]] which was abolished, but losing some constitutional responsibilities to the [[Cabinet Secretary for Government Business and Constitutional Relations]].<ref name=june2018>{{cite web|url=https://news.gov.scot/news/new-cabinet-appointed|title=New Cabinet appointed|publisher=Scottish Government|date=2018-06-26|accessdate=2018-06-27}}</ref> The title was shortened to simply '''Cabinet Secretary for Finance''' in February 2020, with some responsibilities transfered over to the [[Cabinet Secretary for Economy, Fair Work and Culture]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.scot/news/cabinet-appointments/|title=Cabinet Appointments|publisher=Scottish Government|date=17 February 2020}}</ref>\n \n\n==Overview==\n\n===Responsibilities===\nAs Cabinet Secretary for Finance, Economy and Fair Work the responsibilities of the role were:\n\nScottish economy, inclusive growth, managing the public finances, fiscal policy and taxation, Scottish budget, budgetary monitoring and reporting, Government procurement, efficient government, National Performance Framework, public bodies policy, Scottish Futures Trust, Scottish Enterprise - national enterprise agency, trade and inward investment, trade unions, public sector pay, Scottish National Investment Bank, Registers of Scotland, digital economy and digital public services, public sector pensions, Innovation and increasing productivity, internationalisation and European Structural Funds, financial services, life sciences, low carbon economy, business, industry and manufacturing, employment policy, labour market strategy, the living wage and fair work, employability programmes, youth employment (including implementation of the Wood Commission recommendations), women's employment, Bankruptcy and Accountant in Bankruptcy (Scottish government agency), Regional Economic Forums, PACE, Consumer Protection.<ref name=\"june2018\"/>\n\n===Public bodies===\nThe following public bodies reported to the Cabinet Secretary for Finance, Economy and Fair Work:\n* [[Revenue Scotland]]\n* [[Scottish Futures Trust]]\n* [[Scottish National Investment Bank]]\n* [[Scottish Public Pensions Agency]]\n* [[Registers of Scotland]]\n\n==List of Office holders==\n{|class=\"wikitable\"  cellpadding=\"6\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin: 0 0 0 1em; background: #f9f9f9; border: 1px #aaaaaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; \"  \n|colspan=\"7\"|\n\n===Minister for Finance===\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Name\n! width=75|Portrait\n!Entered Office\n!Left Office\n!Party\n!First Minister\n|-\n|{{Scottish politics/party colours/Scottish Labour Party}}|\n|[[Jack McConnell]]\n| [[File:Jack McConnell.jpg|75px]]\n|19 May 1999\n|26 October 2000   \n|[[Scottish Labour Party]]\n\n|[[Donald Dewar]] \n|-\n|colspan=\"7\"|\n\n===Minister for Finance and Local Government===\n|-\n|{{Scottish politics/party colours/Scottish Labour Party}}|\n|[[Angus MacKay (Scottish politician)|Angus Mackay]]\n\n| [[File:Angus MacKay.jpg|75px]]\n|26 October 2000\n|22 November 2001   \n|[[Scottish Labour Party]]\n\n|[[Henry McLeish]]  \n|-\n|colspan=\"7\"|\n\n===Minister for Finance and Public Services===\n|-\n|{{Scottish politics/party colours/Scottish Labour Party}}|\n|[[Andy Kerr (Scottish politician)|Andy Kerr]]\n\n| [[File:Andy Kerr.jpg|75px]]\n|22 November 2001\n|4 October 2004   \n|[[Scottish Labour Party]]\n\n|[[Jack McConnell]]  \n|-\n|colspan=\"7\"|\n\n===Minister for Finance and Public Service Reform===\n|-\n|{{Scottish politics/party colours/Scottish Labour Party}}|\n|[[Tom McCabe]]\n\n| [[File:Tom McCabe.jpg|75px]]\n|4 October 2004\n|16 May 2007   \n|[[Scottish Labour Party]]\n\n|[[Jack McConnell]]  \n|-\n|colspan=\"7\"|\n\n===Cabinet Secretary for Finance and Sustainable Growth===\n|-\n|{{Scottish politics/party colours/Scottish National Party}}|\n|[[John Swinney]]\n\n| [[File:John Swinney, Cabinet Secretary for Sustainable Growth (1).jpg|75px]]\n|     17 May 2007\n|19 May 2011\n|[[Scottish National Party]]\n\n|[[Alex Salmond]]\n|-\n|colspan=\"7\"|\n